⸻

Settle in.

Sit or lie down.
Let your body be supported.
No need to hold yourself up.

Take a slow breath in through your nose…
…and a longer breath out.

Again—
inhale…
exhale slower.

⸻

Now bring your attention to your breathing.

Don’t change it yet.
Just notice it.

Where do you feel it most?
Chest… stomach… throat…

No judgment. Just observation.

⸻

Now begin to guide it.

Inhale through your nose for 4…
2…3…4…

Exhale for 6…
2…3…4…5…6…

Again.

Inhale…
Exhale longer…

⸻

As you breathe, feel your body start to drop.

Shoulders soften.
Jaw unclenches.
Tongue relaxes.

Your face doesn’t need to perform.

⸻

Now shift your awareness slightly wider.

Instead of just the breath…
notice your whole body.

Weight… pressure… contact points…

You are not trying to change anything.

You are just watching.

⸻

If there’s tension… or discomfort…

don’t fight it.

Just place your attention on it.

And breathe.

⸻

Notice something:

The sensation is there…

…but there is also a part of you watching it.

Stay with that.

⸻

You are not the tension.

You are the one observing it.

⸻

Now deepen the breath slightly.

Inhale… steady…

Exhale… slower… longer…

⸻

With each exhale, imagine space opening.

Not forcing anything away—
just creating room around it.

⸻

Now bring in a subtle control.

On the inhale:
feel your body expand.

On the exhale:
feel your system settle.

⸻

You are setting the rhythm.

Not forcing. Not chasing.

Just regulating.

⸻

If thoughts come up…
let them pass like background noise.

No need to follow them.

Return to breath.
Return to awareness.

⸻

Now sit in this state for a moment.

Breathing steady.
Body calm.
Mind watching.

⸻

This is the space.

Not lost.
Not dissociated.

Present, but not reactive.

⸻

Take one deeper breath in…

…and a slow full exhale.

⸻

Gently bring your awareness back.

Move your fingers slightly.
Open your eyes when ready.

